In the use of precious metals such as Pt and Ir, and base metals such as Ni, kinetics and reaction mechanisms are important in considering activity and selectivity as a catalyst. Akram et al. [19] used a number of kinetic equations derived from power-law kinetics and Langmuir–Hinshelwood-Hougen-Watson (LHHW) kinetics to determine the kinetic models for MCH dehydrogenation over monometallic and bimetallic Pt-supported-Al2O3 catalysts. They show that the kinetic model based on the single-site surface reaction mechanism [Eqns. (2–6)] best reproduces the experimental data and that the "the loss of first molecular hydrogen" step in Eq. 3 is the rate-limiting step.2C7H14+σ⇌C7H14·σ\documentclass[12pt]{minimal}
